 prog rock, he argues that metaphors of perfection do justice to neither the perceived strengths nor the assumed weaknesses of the music in question. Instead, he proposes an alternative model of appreciation where abstract notions of virtue need not dictate our understanding. Good music can, with pride, be playful rather than serious, diverse rather than unified, engaging to both body and mind, in dialogue with manifold styles and genres, and collaborative to the core. We can widen the scope of what music we value and reconsider the conventional rituals surrounding it, while retaining the joys of making music, listening closely, and caring passionately.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aMusic-Philosophy and aesthetics. 0aPopular music and art music. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aBruce Springsteen.  aGeorge Frideric Handel.  aGustav Mahler.  aLudwig van Beethoven.  agood music.  ajazz.  amarginalized music.  aprogressive rock.  athe Beatles.  avaluing music.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226593418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226593418/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles